import{_ as e,c as a,o as d,af as n,aE as r,aF as o}from"./chunks/framework.BGH8TCgI.js";const A=JSON.parse('{"title":"Serverless Computing","description":"","frontmatter":{"layout":"doc"},"headers":[],"relativePath":"docs/aws/cloud-practioner/module3/index.md","filePath":"docs/aws/cloud-practioner/module3/index.md"}'),s={name:"docs/aws/cloud-practioner/module3/index.md"};function i(l,t,g,c,m,u){return d(),a("div",null,[...t[0]||(t[0]=[n('<h1 id="serverless-computing" tabindex="-1">Serverless Computing <a class="header-anchor" href="#serverless-computing" aria-label="Permalink to “Serverless Computing”">​</a></h1><h2 id="introduction" tabindex="-1">Introduction <a class="header-anchor" href="#introduction" aria-label="Permalink to “Introduction”">​</a></h2><div class="info custom-block"><p class="custom-block-title">Lesson Plan</p><p><strong>In this lesson, you will learn how to do the following:</strong></p><ul><li>Describe the differences between unmanaged, managed, and serverless compute services in AWS.</li><li>Describe the customer and AWS responsibilities regarding serverless computing.</li></ul></div><p>With serverless computing, you run applications without managing the underlying infrastructure. In the following lessons, you learn how to take full advantage of it with powerful compute services. You explore AWS Lambda, a serverless solution that automatically handles scaling, availability, and maintenance. You also discover services like Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS), Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS), and AWS Elastic Beanstalk, which make container management and application deployment more manageable. After completing these lessons, you will be ready to choose the best one for your needs.</p><p>In these next lessons, you will learn about AWS compute services and the different levels of control they offer. You’ve seen how Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (Amazon EC2), an unmanaged service, gives you full control over virtual machines. Now, you will learn about managed and serverless services that reduce infrastructure management so you can focus on your application.</p><h3 id="key-takeaways" tabindex="-1">Key takeaways: <a class="header-anchor" href="#key-takeaways" aria-label="Permalink to “Key takeaways:”">​</a></h3><p>AWS offers both unmanaged and managed services to suit different levels of control and responsibility. By understanding this model, you will know which tasks AWS manages and which you are responsible for, helping you secure and manage your cloud resources effectively.</p><h4 id="unmanaged-and-managed-services" tabindex="-1">Unmanaged and managed services <a class="header-anchor" href="#unmanaged-and-managed-services" aria-label="Permalink to “Unmanaged and managed services”">​</a></h4><p>With unmanaged compute services like Amazon EC2, AWS takes care of the underlying physical infrastructure, but you&#39;re responsible for setting up, securing, and maintaining the operating system, network configurations, and applications on your instances. Managed services, on the other hand, reduce the amount of infrastructure you need to manage. While AWS handles much of the operational overhead, you might still need to perform some provisioning or configuration depending on the service. <p style="background-color:white;"><img style="padding-block:1rem;" src="'+r+'"></p></p><h4 id="fully-managed-services" tabindex="-1">Fully-managed services <a class="header-anchor" href="#fully-managed-services" aria-label="Permalink to “Fully-managed services”">​</a></h4><p>Fully-managed services—like serverless ones—take abstraction even further, eliminating the need to provision or manage any servers at all. The underlying infrastructure is fully managed by AWS, so you can focus entirely on writing and deploying code. Later in this module, you will explore Lambda. Lambda is a serverless compute service where AWS handles the infrastructure, scaling, and availability, while you remain responsible for securing and managing your application code.</p><p style="background-color:white;"><img style="padding-block:1rem;" src="'+o+'"></p><div class="info custom-block"><p class="custom-block-title">Managed vs Unmanaged Services</p><p>With unmanaged services like Amazon EC2, you set up and manage everything: the operating system, security updates, and network settings. AWS only takes care of the physical hardware. Managed services handle most of the infrastructure for you, but you still need to set up things like deployment options, scaling, and environment settings. With fully managed services like AWS Lambda, you don’t manage any servers at all. You upload your code, and AWS takes care of the rest, including infrastructure, scaling, and availability.</p></div><h1 id="aws-services-by-management-level" tabindex="-1">AWS Services by Management Level <a class="header-anchor" href="#aws-services-by-management-level" aria-label="Permalink to “AWS Services by Management Level”">​</a></h1><table tabindex="0"><thead><tr><th><strong>Fully Managed (Serverless)</strong></th><th><strong>Managed</strong></th><th><strong>Unmanaged</strong></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>AWS Lambda</strong> - Serverless compute with no server provisioning; AWS handles infrastructure, scaling, and availability</td><td><strong>Amazon RDS</strong> - Managed relational database; AWS handles patching, backups, and maintenance, but you configure database settings</td><td><strong>Amazon EC2</strong> - Virtual servers where you manage OS, security patches, network configs, and applications</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AWS Fargate</strong> - Serverless container compute; no need to manage servers or clusters</td><td><strong>Amazon ECS (with EC2)</strong> - Container orchestration where AWS manages the control plane, but you manage the underlying EC2 instances</td><td><strong>EC2 with self-managed databases</strong> - Complete control and responsibility for all software and configurations</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Amazon S3</strong> - Object storage with automatic scaling and no infrastructure management</td><td><strong>Amazon ElastiCache</strong> - Managed in-memory cache; AWS handles patching and backups, but you configure clusters</td><td><strong>EC2 with self-installed software</strong> - Manual installation and maintenance of all applications</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Amazon DynamoDB</strong> - Serverless NoSQL database with automatic scaling</td><td><strong>Amazon EMR</strong> - Managed big data platform; AWS manages cluster setup, but you configure cluster size and applications</td><td><strong>Self-managed Kubernetes on EC2</strong> - Complete control over container orchestration and infrastructure</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AWS Step Functions</strong> - Serverless workflow orchestration</td><td><strong>Amazon MQ</strong> - Managed message broker; AWS handles maintenance, but you manage broker configurations</td><td><strong>VMs with manual load balancing</strong> - Self-configured networking and traffic management</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Amazon API Gateway</strong> - Fully managed API service with automatic scaling</td><td><strong>AWS Batch</strong> - Managed batch processing; AWS manages compute resources, but you define job parameters</td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Amazon EventBridge</strong> - Serverless event bus</td><td><strong>Amazon OpenSearch Service</strong> - Managed search and analytics; AWS handles infrastructure, but you manage indices and queries</td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>AWS AppSync</strong> - Fully managed GraphQL service</td><td><strong>Amazon EKS</strong> - Managed Kubernetes control plane; AWS manages masters, but you manage worker nodes</td><td></td></tr></tbody></table><h2 id="key-differences" tabindex="-1">Key Differences <a class="header-anchor" href="#key-differences" aria-label="Permalink to “Key Differences”">​</a></h2><ul><li><strong>Fully Managed/Serverless</strong>: AWS handles infrastructure, scaling, patching, and availability. You focus solely on code and configuration.</li><li><strong>Managed</strong>: AWS handles much of the operational overhead (patching, backups, infrastructure), but you still provision, configure, and may maintain some components.</li><li><strong>Unmanaged</strong>: You have full control and responsibility for the OS, security, networking, applications, and all maintenance tasks. AWS only manages the physical hardware layer.</li></ul><h3 id="but-that-is-not-all-there-is-more" tabindex="-1">But that is not all... There is more! <a class="header-anchor" href="#but-that-is-not-all-there-is-more" aria-label="Permalink to “But that is not all... There is more!”">​</a></h3><p>You&#39;re absolutely right! AWS has hundreds of services. Let me create a much more comprehensive breakdown:</p><h2 id="aws-services-by-management-level-1" tabindex="-1">AWS Services by Management Level <a class="header-anchor" href="#aws-services-by-management-level-1" aria-label="Permalink to “AWS Services by Management Level”">​</a></h2><table tabindex="0"><thead><tr><th><strong>Fully Managed (Serverless)</strong></th><th><strong>Managed</strong></th><th><strong>Unmanaged</strong></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Compute</strong></td><td><strong>Compute</strong></td><td><strong>Compute</strong></td></tr><tr><td>AWS Lambda</td><td>Amazon ECS (with EC2)</td><td>Amazon EC2</td></tr><tr><td>AWS Fargate</td><td>Amazon EKS</td><td>EC2 with self-managed software</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS Batch</td><td>EC2 Bare Metal instances</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS Elastic Beanstalk</td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Storage</strong></td><td><strong>Storage</strong></td><td><strong>Storage</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon S3</td><td>Amazon EFS</td><td>EC2 with attached EBS (self-managed)</td></tr><tr><td>Amazon S3 Glacier</td><td>Amazon FSx</td><td>Self-configured storage solutions</td></tr><tr><td>Amazon EFS (serverless option)</td><td>AWS Storage Gateway</td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS Backup</td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Database</strong></td><td><strong>Database</strong></td><td><strong>Database</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon DynamoDB</td><td>Amazon RDS (all engines)</td><td>Databases installed on EC2</td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Aurora Serverless</td><td>Amazon Aurora (provisioned)</td><td>Self-managed MySQL, PostgreSQL, etc.</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Amazon Redshift</td><td>MongoDB on EC2</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Amazon ElastiCache</td><td>Redis/Memcached on EC2</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Amazon Neptune</td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Amazon DocumentDB</td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Amazon Keyspaces (Cassandra)</td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Amazon Timestream</td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Amazon QLDB</td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Networking &amp; Content Delivery</strong></td><td><strong>Networking &amp; Content Delivery</strong></td><td><strong>Networking</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon CloudFront</td><td>AWS Global Accelerator</td><td>VPC with custom routing</td></tr><tr><td>Amazon API Gateway</td><td>Elastic Load Balancing (ALB, NLB, CLB)</td><td>Self-managed load balancers on EC2</td></tr><tr><td>AWS AppSync</td><td>Amazon Route 53</td><td>Custom DNS on EC2</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS Direct Connect</td><td>Self-configured VPNs</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS Transit Gateway</td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS VPN</td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Analytics</strong></td><td><strong>Analytics</strong></td><td><strong>Analytics</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Athena</td><td>Amazon EMR</td><td>Hadoop/Spark on EC2</td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Kinesis Data Analytics</td><td>Amazon Redshift</td><td>Self-managed data warehouses</td></tr><tr><td>Amazon QuickSight</td><td>Amazon Kinesis Data Streams</td><td>Kafka on EC2</td></tr><tr><td>AWS Glue</td><td>Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose</td><td>Custom ETL on EC2</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Amazon MSK (Managed Kafka)</td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS Data Pipeline</td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS Lake Formation</td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Amazon OpenSearch Service</td><td>Elasticsearch on EC2</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application Integration</strong></td><td><strong>Application Integration</strong></td><td><strong>Application Integration</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon EventBridge</td><td>Amazon MQ</td><td>RabbitMQ on EC2</td></tr><tr><td>Amazon SNS</td><td>Amazon SQS (managed but configurable)</td><td>Custom message queues</td></tr><tr><td>Amazon SQS</td><td>AWS Step Functions (some configs)</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>AWS Step Functions</td><td>Amazon AppFlow</td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Developer Tools</strong></td><td><strong>Developer Tools</strong></td><td><strong>Developer Tools</strong></td></tr><tr><td>AWS Amplify</td><td>AWS CodeBuild</td><td>Jenkins on EC2</td></tr><tr><td>AWS Cloud9</td><td>AWS CodeDeploy</td><td>GitLab on EC2</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS CodePipeline</td><td>Self-hosted CI/CD</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS CodeCommit</td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS CodeArtifact</td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Management &amp; Governance</strong></td><td><strong>Management &amp; Governance</strong></td><td><strong>Management</strong></td></tr><tr><td>AWS CloudFormation</td><td>AWS Systems Manager</td><td>Custom configuration management</td></tr><tr><td>AWS CloudTrail</td><td>AWS CloudWatch</td><td>Self-hosted monitoring</td></tr><tr><td>AWS Config</td><td>AWS OpsWorks</td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS Service Catalog</td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS Control Tower</td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS Organizations</td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Security, Identity &amp; Compliance</strong></td><td><strong>Security, Identity &amp; Compliance</strong></td><td><strong>Security</strong></td></tr><tr><td>AWS IAM</td><td>AWS Certificate Manager</td><td>Self-signed certificates</td></tr><tr><td>AWS Secrets Manager</td><td>AWS WAF</td><td>Custom firewalls on EC2</td></tr><tr><td>AWS Key Management Service (KMS)</td><td>AWS Shield Standard/Advanced</td><td>Self-managed security tools</td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Cognito</td><td>Amazon GuardDuty</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Macie</td><td>AWS Security Hub</td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Amazon Inspector</td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS Firewall Manager</td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Machine Learning</strong></td><td><strong>Machine Learning</strong></td><td><strong>Machine Learning</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Rekognition</td><td>Amazon SageMaker</td><td>TensorFlow/PyTorch on EC2</td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Comprehend</td><td>AWS Deep Learning AMIs</td><td>Custom ML pipelines</td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Translate</td><td>Amazon Bedrock (some configs)</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Polly</td><td>Amazon Kendra</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Transcribe</td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Textract</td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Lex</td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Forecast</td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Personalize</td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Media Services</strong></td><td><strong>Media Services</strong></td><td><strong>Media</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Kinesis Video Streams</td><td>AWS Elemental MediaConvert</td><td>FFmpeg on EC2</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS Elemental MediaLive</td><td>Custom streaming servers</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS Elemental MediaPackage</td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>IoT</strong></td><td><strong>IoT</strong></td><td><strong>IoT</strong></td></tr><tr><td>AWS IoT Core</td><td>AWS IoT Greengrass</td><td>Custom IoT on EC2</td></tr><tr><td>AWS IoT Analytics</td><td>AWS IoT Device Management</td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>AWS IoT Events</td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Game Development</strong></td><td><strong>Game Development</strong></td><td><strong>Game Development</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon GameLift (FleetIQ)</td><td>Amazon GameLift (managed)</td><td>Game servers on EC2</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Business Applications</strong></td><td><strong>Business Applications</strong></td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Connect</td><td>Amazon WorkSpaces</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Chime</td><td>Amazon WorkDocs</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon SES</td><td>Amazon WorkMail</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Pinpoint</td><td>Amazon AppStream 2.0</td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>End User Computing</strong></td><td><strong>End User Computing</strong></td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Amazon WorkSpaces</td><td>Virtual desktops on EC2</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Amazon AppStream 2.0</td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Amazon WorkSpaces Web</td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Blockchain</strong></td><td><strong>Blockchain</strong></td><td><strong>Blockchain</strong></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Amazon Managed Blockchain</td><td>Hyperledger on EC2</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Quantum Computing</strong></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Amazon Braket</td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Satellite</strong></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td>AWS Ground Station</td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Robotics</strong></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td>AWS RoboMaker</td><td></td><td></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>Note</strong>: This is still not exhaustive—AWS has 200+ services and continues to add more. The classification can sometimes be nuanced, as some services offer both managed and serverless options (like Aurora or EFS), and the level of management responsibility can vary based on configuration choices.</p>',22)])])}const p=e(s,[["render",i]]);export{A as __pageData,p as default};
